title: Let users specify/go to exact window time range
body:
Migrating issue from: https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=582531

-----

**Original description:**

This is a feature request to be able to set the start & end timestamps of the window time range OR a start timestamp and window span value. This would be useful when we want to jump to a specific section of the trace, for example when we know through other means (e.g., logs, babeltrace output timestamps) that we want to visualize a specific section. This would also be useful when we want to reliably/consistently set the window time range, e.g., for taking screenshots, etc.

The histogram view allows setting selection start & end timestamps and a window span value [1], but it's not quite the same given that it is the selection range and not the window range. Furthermore, this feature request isn't really about the histogram view specifically. It applies to any view with a typical time axis.

This feature could be implemented as a simple dialog with text boxes for start & end timestamp OR start timestamp and window span that is opened by:

1. A keyboard shortcut
2. Double-clicking on the timestamps shown in the lower left corner
3. Right-clicking on a view's time axis values and clicking on something like "Set window time range"
4. Or some other mechanism

I could probably contribute this feature, but I just need us to agree on the exact mechanism and whether this feature would be welcome.


[1] https://archive.eclipse.org/tracecompass/doc/stable/org.eclipse.tracecompass.doc.user/Trace-Compass-Main-Features.html#Histogram_View

----

**Comment from Bernd Hufmann:**

Hi Christophe

this is a interesting feature suggestion. I agree it would be good to have a way to input a specific time range to navigate to. The histogram view has way to specify the selection range. But, to be honest, it should not have been separate from the Histogram view and it only allows to set the selection range.

The Time Graph views, like the Resources view allow to zoom to a window range that is currently selected by pressing the Z keyboard button. This is good, but it require such a view to be open.

Having an separate window for specifying the window range would be good. Not sure what is the best UX. For sure such a feature needs to be easily discoverable by the user. A dialog or a so called "Fast View" of Eclipse could be a way. 

You could decide to allow to specify the selection window and have a button and Keyboard short (e.g. Z) cut to zoom to that selection. 

If you could come up with a proposal implementation would be highly appreciated, because currently we don't have the bandwidth to work on it. Maybe let it try by your users to give feedback and then we can review it and give our feedback.

Thanks a lot for your initiative.

Bernd

----

**Comment from Ivan Grinenko:**

Hi,

This is a very nice to have feature. As for me I see it implemented as something global (a key combination, or a button on a toolbar of a supported view). By 'global' I mean it should apply the selected time range to all the views having the 'Align Views' option eneabled.

Thanks!

title: Time Graph filter doesn't support list of values in matches statements
body:
The time graph filter doesn't support list of values in matches statements. For example, using the Resources view with a LTTng kernel trace, the filter string `CPU matches [0,1]` doesn't match anything and by default everything is shown and non-matching CPU rows are not dimmed. On the contrary, value ranges, like `CPU matches [0-1]` will highlight matching CPU rows and dim the rest. 


![rcv-cpu-filtering-bug](https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass/org.eclipse.tracecompass/assets/413424/172c22b2-5b53-45cf-a03d-eff57084bd6f)

title: NA
body: The bug is that `,` is not considered as a valid character for a text sequence. For that reason the ANTLR parser is not able to parse the input string and hence it's not passed on as regular expression pattern to be used for matching. So, the solution is to add `,` in the ANTLR grammar.

title: Time Graph filter doesn't support regex groups matches statements
body:
The time graph filter doesn't support regex groups in matches statements. For example, using the Resources view with a LTTng kernel trace, the filter string `CPU matches (0|1)` doesn't match anything and by default everything is shown and non-matching CPU rows are not dimmed. On the contrary, the following filter `CPU matches [0]|[1]` will highlight matching CPU rows and dim the rest.

![rcv-cpu-filtering-bug2](https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass/org.eclipse.tracecompass/assets/413424/29334467-3415-454c-8b0e-b60d114393cd)

title: NA
body:
Regex grouping is not required for searching and filtering. The example used in description can be achieved with the brackets. Groupings can also be achieved in root expression, for example `(CPU matches 0) || (CPU matches 1)`. 

For those reasons, I'm closing the ticket.

body:
I think if you use the Trace Compass RCP release 9.3.0 and install incubator features from https://download.eclipse.org/tracecompass.incubator/master/repository/, then this is error happens, because the update site is not compatible with the 9.3.0 release. Some features were moved from incubator to Trace Compass mainline (incubator callstack) and the 9.3.0 release doesn't have the migrated code. I can reproduce that behaviour on my laptop and it's also happening on Linux and not just Windows.

You will have to use install the incubator features using the `Add-ons` menu or using update site https://download.eclipse.org/tracecompass.incubator/stable-9.3/repository/. 

Unfortunately, that update site is currently broken. I'm working on a fix for that with PR: https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass-incubator/org.eclipse.tracecompass.incubator/pull/29. Once it's merged I can re-build the stable-9.3 updates side.

After that I suggest that you install the incubator features from the `Add-on` menu or from that update-site. (BTW, the `Add-on` uses that update site). You might want to start from a freshly extracted Trace Compass 9.3. RCP zip file.

It's not that hard because you can follow what was done in Trace Compass mainline. However, some changes need to be done in the pom files and CI setup. 

From what I can remember, you will have to add a mac signing and a notarization profile in the RCP product pom.xml. Then add flags to the incubator Jenkinsfile to be enable mac signing. In Trace Compass we have a separate jenkins job that does the notarization (https://ci.eclipse.org/tracecompass/job/notarize-tracecompass-dmgs/) which is triggered after a successful build (e.g. nightly.). It calls a script (notarize-mac.sh) for that.

title: Changing trace type after opening an experiment does not update the experiment
body:
To reproduce the issue:
- Open a trace with type 1
- Create an experiment with this trace
- Change the trace type of the trace to type 2 in the "traces" folder and not in the experiment

The trace in the experiment will display the icon of the type 2 but the trace will still be parsed in the experiment as a type 1.
The issue does not appear when changing the trace directly in the experiment.

The trace in the experiment should keep the icon the type 1.

title: NA
body:
I'm not able to reproduce this error. Changing the trace type of a trace from the traces folder or under the experiment will propagate the change to the trace under the traces folder and all experiments where this trace is part of. It just not changes the icon of the trace (in traces folder and under each experiment) but also changes the persistent property on the trace, that is used when creating the trace instance.

I tested that with a LTTng UST trace.

- Open a trace with type1 (LTTng UST trace type)
- Create an experiment with this trace
- Change the trace type of the trace to type 2 (Generic CTF)  in the "traces" folder and not in the experiment

The icon changes everywhere and only views applicable to Generic CTF traces are shown under the Views folder.

> The Trace in the experiment should keep the icon the type 1

title: EASE Scripting feature fails at initialization
body:
The incubator EASE Scripting feature throws an exception at initialization (e.g. switching to Scripting perspective).

EASE (org.eclipse.ease) has a dependency on org.mozilla.javascript plug-in. Trace Compass is using the latest version of this feature which has been renamed to org.mozilla.rhino, for use with the XML Analysis feature.

When both plug-ins are installed it creates a conflict that causes initialization failure of the RhinoScriptEngine.

Trace Compass needs to downgrade to use the older org.mozilla.javascript plug-in to ensure compatibility with the incubator EASE Scripting feature. This older version can be found in previous Orbit release repositories.

To use the latest version of org.mozilla.rhino plug-in, it will require an update from the EASE project first.

title: Inconsistent field names for time graph views
body:
When [filtering][flt] in time graph views ("/" in the Eclipse
version), the user needs to construct a filter using filter
expressions. The filter expressions in general tests values of fields.

The field names are opaque from a user's perspective, and the names
are not created consistently which makes it harder to guess what
fields are available to filter on.

Some fields use lowercase [("label", "entry")][coremetadata], some use
full upper-case ("CPU", "TID"), and some uppercase the first letter
[("Start Time", "End Time", "Duration")][tmfstrings].

The field names are controlled by each time graph dataprovider and are
sometimes dynamically created which does make it harder to enforce
consistency.

Making the fields provided by [default][timegraphstate] consistently
named would be an improvement to set a standard for other fields
(albeit voluntarily). So the basic TimeGraphState could by default
provide fields like:
- "Label"
- "Start Time"
- "End Time"
- "Duration"

Rather than:
- "label"
- "Start Time"
- "End Time"
- "Duration"

(Or whichever case you prefer)

[flt]: https://archive.eclipse.org/tracecompass/doc/stable/org.eclipse.tracecompass.doc.user/Trace-Compass-Main-Features.html#Filtering_Time_Events_in_Time_Graph_Views
[coremetadata]: https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass/org.eclipse.tracecompass/blob/master/tmf/org.eclipse.tracecompass.tmf.core/src/org/eclipse/tracecompass/tmf/core/model/CoreMetadataStrings.java
[tmfstrings]: https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass/org.eclipse.tracecompass/blob/master/tmf/org.eclipse.tracecompass.tmf.core/src/org/eclipse/tracecompass/internal/tmf/core/messages.properties
[timegraphstate]: https://github.com/eclipse-tracecompass/org.eclipse.tracecompass/blob/620dd63143c671679c69d8d63a20f354cb03dd25/tmf/org.eclipse.tracecompass.tmf.core/src/org/eclipse/tracecompass/tmf/core/model/timegraph/TimeGraphState.java#L129

title: HistoryTreeBackendIterator skips nodes during construction
body:
In HistoryTreeBackendIterator, the time range condition for queuing children nodes is reduced according to the current node time range.

During construction, it can happen that the root node has a time range that is only the start timestamp. In that case the iterator will only consider child nodes that intersect with the start time and all other child nodes will be discarded. The iterator can then miss many intersecting intervals.

The root node time range can be increased if intervals are added to it (this does not always happen) or at the end of construction when the node is closed.

A solution seems to be to avoid reducing the time range condition when the current node is the root node.

title: ThreadedHistoryTreeBackend missing intervals in query2D
body:
In https://git.eclipse.org/r/134665 a 'reverse' parameter was added to the signature of the IStateHistoryBackend.query2D() interface.

The state system was changed to call this new method. But ThreadedHistoryTreeBackend was not updated to implement this method, and therefore the implementation in base class HistoryTreeBackend is used. The base class is not aware of and misses intervals that are currently held in the interval queue (BufferedBlockingQueue) waiting to be written to file.

title: Remote connection to target without JUL daemon does not handle error message gracefully (lttng 2.13)
body:
Recently, we updated our embedded target and apparently liblttng-ust is no longer being built with --enable-java-agent-jul.

When connecting to this target over ssh from TraceCompass, the following error occurs:

```
Error retrieving node configuration
    Command failed! Command: lttng --mi xml list -j
```

Actual output of this command when run on the target:
```
[15:56 ~]# lttng --mi xml list -j
Error: Unable to list jul events: Session daemon agent tracing is disabled
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<command xmlns="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi https://lttng.org/xml/schemas/lttng-mi/4/lttng-mi-4.1.xsd" schemaVersion="4.1"><name>list</name><output/></command>
```

I suspect that the parser is choking on the bare error message emitted before the XML response content.

This can probably be solved by adding the --quiet arg to the request, to suppress the bare error output if the parser is not prepared to handle it:
```
[15:57 ~]# lttng --quiet --mi xml list -j        
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<command xmlns="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi https://lttng.org/xml/schemas/lttng-mi/4/lttng-mi-4.1.xsd" schemaVersion="4.1"><name>list</name><output/></command>
```
or by redirecting stderr to /dev/null:
```
[16:05 ~]# lttng --mi xml list -j 2>/dev/null
<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<command xmlns="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="https://lttng.org/xml/ns/lttng-mi https://lttng.org/xml/schemas/lttng-mi/4/lttng-mi-4.1.xsd" schemaVersion="4.1"><name>list</name><output/></command>
```

To workaround in the short term: Is it possible to disable TraceCompass from querying for JUL domain session list? (via a properties or prefs file, command line arg, etc)  Search didn't turn up any clues...

TraceCompass version: 10.2.0
lttng version on target: 
```
[15:44 ~]# lttng --version
lttng (LTTng Trace Control) 2.13.9 - Nordicité
```

title: NA

body:
### Bug Description:

The symbols for the LTTng-UST cyg profile analysis can appear only when the UstDebugInfoAnalysis is completed. For large traces, it is necessary to wait quite a while before being able to visualize the stack trace.

Also, it is necessary to close and reopen the trace for the symbols to show.

### Steps to Reproduce:

1. Take a large cyg profile trace (>10 million events)
2. Open the trace
3. Symbols do not show

### Additional Information

This is because the UstDebugInfoAnalysisModule.getMatchingFile does a full query to get the debug binary information. However, the information has not yet been written into the backend as the interval is closed only at the end of the trace.

title: Callstack should show reason when symbols cannot be provided
body:
### Bug Description:

The symbols for the LTTng-UST cyg profile analysis sometimes cannot be provided as some information is missing (vpid, vtid missing), binary not found, etc...
Trace Compass should show somewhere why it is the case and should point to the documentation on how to resolve that issue.

### Additional Information

The issue most often is the UstDebugInfoBinaryAspect cannot provide the BinaryCallsite for different reasons. The reason is not escalated and null is returned.

title: CallGraph analysis does not save its result on disk
body:
### Bug Description:

Currently a cache is maintained in the FlameGraphDataProvider, saving the result of the callgraph analysis in an in memory state system.  This should be saved by the CallGraphAnalysis because this result could be saved on disk and avoid recomputing the callgraph when reopening the trace.

### Steps to Reproduce:

1. Running any analysis providing a call graph
2. Closing the trace
3. Reopening and opening the flamegraph makes it compute the callgraph again.

title: Performance impact of mxbeans on logging
CTF Trace - Metadata template
body:
Good Afternoon,

I am trying to parse a CTF trace with Trace Compass. I have saved both the metadata and trace files in a directory and imported it by using the Project Explorer. I did obtain a visualization of my data, but I can't seem to get it to populate the control flow view.

Expected:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/81d1dfb6-9beb-46d5-b2de-0c6dc7ad26fd)

Actual:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/7ae3ec70-78c1-44a6-b9b6-6767106fbaf5)

Although this is probably caused by the timestamps having all the same value, i was still hoping for a depiction of the idle time.

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/d0095321-45ce-4cd8-9386-f0f634858d57)

I am now trying to understand why the "blocks" of events are generated together and at a constant interval of .510 seconds. In the meantime, may I ask if Trace Compass has certain requirements for the CTF metadata? Is there a metadata-template to follow or should the tool be able to correctly depict the events regardless of how their fields are named / ordered?

Thank you very much for your time

title: NA
body:
>I am now trying to understand why the "blocks" of events are generated together and at a constant interval of .510 seconds. In the meantime, may I ask if Trace Compass has certain requirements for the CTF metadata? Is there a metadata-template to follow or should the tool be able to correctly depict the events regardless of how their fields are named / ordered?

The `Control Flow View` is specific to Linux Kernel traces, e.g. LTTng, FTrace or Perf (converted to CTF). It requires certain trace events and fields to be able to populate it. 

If your trace content can be mapped to those Linux Kernel events and fields, then you could implement a Trace Compass plug-in extension that implements `IKernelTrace`. You will have to provide a so called `IKernelAnalysisEventLayout` to map your trace events to the required format. This is done when post processing the trace file in Trace Compass.

This would need to be done in as a plug-in extension in Java and installed on top of the Trace Compass application. See Trace Compass developer guide for more details on writing a plug-in extension: https://archive.eclipse.org/tracecompass/doc/stable/org.eclipse.tracecompass.doc.dev/Developer-Guide.html
Note: Browse the source code for `IKernelTrace` and `IKernelAnalysisEventLayout` and how it's used.

Alternatively, you could create such view from scratch a plug-in extension. Trace Compass has a lot of APIs to help with that. See the developer guide above for this as well. 

If don't want to write Java code, you could use the data-driven analysis and view capabilities of Trace Compass. You can define the state machine in XML and define the view mapping in XML as well. This will populate such view. Here is some documentation:
https://archive.eclipse.org/tracecompass/doc/stable/org.eclipse.tracecompass.doc.user/Data-driven-analysis.html#Data_driven_analysis

Lastly, you could use EASE scripting to create such view. Here is a tutorial on how to do that: 
https://github.com/dorsal-lab/Tracevizlab/tree/master/labs/204-scripted-analysis-for-custom-instrumentation
